<paragraph blockId="64.[147,1463,1902,2099]" pageId="64" pageNumber="217">
Text-fig. 41. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of monocolpate pollen of 
<taxonomicName authority="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen, 2019" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2019" box="[1021,1218,1902,1923]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Piercipollis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="64" pageNumber="217" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="simplex" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1021,1218,1902,1923]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="217">Piercipollis simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1226,1383,1902,1923]" pageId="64" pageNumber="217" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from a pollen clump; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; pollen clump that yielded the pollen in this Text-figure; b–d) Pollen grains in distal (b), proximal (c) and lateral views (d) showing the very long colpus and the well-developed reticulum that is only loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer; note the large angular lumina, smooth muri and short, sparsely scattered, columellae; note also that main body of pollen grains (foot layer) does not fill out the whole space of the reticulum; e) Reticulum showing the smooth muri loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer by short, sparsely scattered, columellae. Specimen, TV44-S136755 (holotype). Scale bars 300 Μm (a), 6 Μm (b–d), 3 Μm (e).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="65.[106,745,151,207]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">E t y m o l o g y. From Latin: simplex referring to the simple reticulum and colpus margin.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[106,744,231,287]" box="[144,744,231,255]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">T y p e l o c a l i t y. Torres Vedras (NE of Forte de</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[106,744,231,287]" box="[106,469,261,287]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">
Forca; 
<geoCoordinate box="[181,317,261,286]" degrees="39" direction="north" minutes="06" orientation="latitude" pageId="65" pageNumber="218" precision="15" seconds="13" value="39.10361">39°06′13″ N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[328,457,261,287]" degrees="9" direction="west" minutes="14" orientation="longitude" pageId="65" pageNumber="218" precision="15" seconds="47" value="-9.246389">9°14′47″ W</geoCoordinate>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[106,745,310,398]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">T y p e s t r a t u m a n d a g e. Lower member of the Almargem Formation; Early Cretaceous (late Barremianearly Aptian).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[144,493,421,445]" box="[144,493,421,445]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">D i a g n o s i s. As for the genus.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[144,744,468,492]" box="[144,744,468,492]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">D i m e n s i o n s. Length of pollen grains: about 15 µm.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[106,745,515,1051]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">
D e s c r i p t i o n a n d r e m a r k s. The species is based on four pollen clumps containing many pollen grains of the same kind. The pollen clumps are perhaps fragments of anthers (
<figureCitation box="[222,361,611,635]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="64.[147,228,1902,1923]" captionTargetBox="[151,1463,685,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-256@64.[367,1019,684,1303]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Text-fig. 41. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of monocolpate pollen of Piercipollis simplex gen. et sp. nov. from a pollen clump; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; pollen clump that yielded the pollen in this Text-figure; b–d) Pollen grains in distal (b), proximal (c) and lateral views (d) showing the very long colpus and the well-developed reticulum that is only loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer; note the large angular lumina, smooth muri and short, sparsely scattered, columellae; note also that main body of pollen grains (foot layer) does not fill out the whole space of the reticulum; e) Reticulum showing the smooth muri loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer by short, sparsely scattered, columellae. Specimen, TV44-S136755 (holotype). Scale bars 300 Μm (a), 6 Μm (b–d), 3 Μm (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386339/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">Text-fig. 41a</figureCitation>
). The pollen grains are small, almost circular in equatorial outline, about 15 µm in diameter, and monocolpate. The colpus is long, extending to the equator. The exine is semitectate-reticulate and columellate (Textfig. 41b–d). The reticulum is coarse, homobrochate and with polygonal to rounded lumina up to about 0.35 µm wide (
<figureCitation box="[113,254,803,827]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="64.[147,228,1902,1923]" captionTargetBox="[151,1463,685,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-256@64.[367,1019,684,1303]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Text-fig. 41. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of monocolpate pollen of Piercipollis simplex gen. et sp. nov. from a pollen clump; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; pollen clump that yielded the pollen in this Text-figure; b–d) Pollen grains in distal (b), proximal (c) and lateral views (d) showing the very long colpus and the well-developed reticulum that is only loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer; note the large angular lumina, smooth muri and short, sparsely scattered, columellae; note also that main body of pollen grains (foot layer) does not fill out the whole space of the reticulum; e) Reticulum showing the smooth muri loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer by short, sparsely scattered, columellae. Specimen, TV44-S136755 (holotype). Scale bars 300 Μm (a), 6 Μm (b–d), 3 Μm (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386339/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">Text-fig. 41e</figureCitation>
). The muri are smooth with a slightly rounded profile and are supported by long scattered columellae. The colpus is distinctly delimited by a continuous line formed by the marginal muri of the reticulum. There is no difference in the form of the reticulum close to the colpus compared to over the main body of the grain (
<figureCitation box="[507,681,963,987]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="64.[147,228,1902,1923]" captionTargetBox="[151,1463,685,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-256@64.[367,1019,684,1303]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Text-fig. 41. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of monocolpate pollen of Piercipollis simplex gen. et sp. nov. from a pollen clump; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; pollen clump that yielded the pollen in this Text-figure; b–d) Pollen grains in distal (b), proximal (c) and lateral views (d) showing the very long colpus and the well-developed reticulum that is only loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer; note the large angular lumina, smooth muri and short, sparsely scattered, columellae; note also that main body of pollen grains (foot layer) does not fill out the whole space of the reticulum; e) Reticulum showing the smooth muri loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer by short, sparsely scattered, columellae. Specimen, TV44-S136755 (holotype). Scale bars 300 Μm (a), 6 Μm (b–d), 3 Μm (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386339/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">Text-fig. 41b, d</figureCitation>
). The reticulum is often detached from, and larger than, the main body of the pollen grain (
<figureCitation box="[376,546,1027,1051]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="64.[147,228,1902,1923]" captionTargetBox="[151,1463,685,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-256@64.[367,1019,684,1303]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Text-fig. 41. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of monocolpate pollen of Piercipollis simplex gen. et sp. nov. from a pollen clump; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; pollen clump that yielded the pollen in this Text-figure; b–d) Pollen grains in distal (b), proximal (c) and lateral views (d) showing the very long colpus and the well-developed reticulum that is only loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer; note the large angular lumina, smooth muri and short, sparsely scattered, columellae; note also that main body of pollen grains (foot layer) does not fill out the whole space of the reticulum; e) Reticulum showing the smooth muri loosely attached to the smooth surface of the foot layer by short, sparsely scattered, columellae. Specimen, TV44-S136755 (holotype). Scale bars 300 Μm (a), 6 Μm (b–d), 3 Μm (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386339/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">Text-fig. 41b–d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[106,744,1074,1226]" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">
A f f i n i t y a n d o t h e r o c c u r r e n c e s. A single pollen grain similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2019" box="[366,582,1106,1130]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Piercipollis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="65" pageNumber="218" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[366,582,1106,1130]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">Piercipollis simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also been observed in a coprolite from the Catefica locality, but otherwise the species is unknown from other mesofossil floras in 
<collectingCountry box="[199,293,1202,1226]" name="Portugal" pageId="65" pageNumber="218">Portugal</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
